hether a specific tracepoint<br />&gt; is stable if the kernel code doesn't document that it's stable?<br /><br />You are living in some unrealistic dream-world where you think you can<br />get the right tracepoint on the first try.<br /><br />So there is no way in hell I would ever mark any tracepoint "stable"<br />until it has had a fair amount of use, and there are useful tools that<br />actually make use of it, and it has shown itself to be the right<br />trace-point.<br /><br />And once that actually happens, what's the advantage of marking it<br />stable? None. It's a catch-22. Before it has uses and has been tested<br />and found to be good, it's not stable. And after, it's pointless.<br /><br />So at no point does such a "stable" tracepoint marking make sense. At<br />most, you end up adding a comment saying "this tracepoint is used by<br />tools such-and-such".<br /><br />                   Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
